[2026-03-18T18:19:00.030Z] [STDOUT] {"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-opus-4-6","id":"msg_01DWwKrhtFHvis5KpmGWByV1","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"text","text":"All 5 ideas saved successfully. Here's a summary:\n\n## Feature Scout Results — Trigger Scheduling\n\n**5 ideas created** (saved to Vibeman):\n\n| # | Title | Category | Effort | Impact | Risk |\n|---|-------|----------|--------|--------|------|\n| 1 | Missed-trigger catch-up policy on scheduler restart | functionality | 4 | 8 | 4 |\n| 2 | Active time-window constraints for triggers | functionality | 5 | 7 | 3 |\n| 3 | Trigger-level concurrency guard (skip-if-running) | functionality | 5 | 8 | 4 |\n| 4 | Per-trigger fire history API with stats | functionality | 4 | 7 | 2 |\n| 5 | Scheduler observability in health endpoint | user_benefit | 3 | 7 | 2 |\n\n### Key Observations\n\n- The trigger scheduler uses a well-implemented min-heap (`TriggerHeap`) that avoids full DB scans — the core scheduling mechanics are solid.\n- The biggest gap vs. mature schedulers (Airflow, Temporal, K8s CronJobs) is the **lack of fire-time policies** — no catch-up, no concurrency guards, no active windows.\n- The `/health` endpoint is comprehensive for workers/DB/Kafka but **completely blind to the scheduler** — a quick win for operational visibility.\n- Trigger debugging requires manual correlation across events and executions; a **dedicated fire history endpoint** would be table-stakes for the category."}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":3096,"cache_read_input_tokens":56919,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":3096},"output_tokens":1,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"18cf733e-5086-44f8-9b8f-c7145785d79c","uuid":"10515655-91f2-4355-b0a8-0d7c02a805e1"}
